data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated collection and assertion APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, count)`** — on failure shows *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"IsTrue failed"*. Note: expected value goes first.
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** — clearer intent than `IsTrue(x != null)`.
- **Message parameter** on `IsTrue` — explains *what* was expected when LINQ predicates fail.
- **Removed `users.Count > 0`** — redundant since `AreEqual(3, ...)` already covers it.

**Also consider `CollectionAssert`** for richer scenarios:

```csharp
// Assert no nulls in collection
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// Assert all items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Assert collections have same elements (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedUsers, users);

// Assert exact order match
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedUsers, users);
```

These give far more diagnostic output on failure than `Assert.IsTrue` with LINQ.
